As Martin's solo career grew, he and Frank Sinatra became friends. In the late 1950s
and early 1960s, Martin and Sinatra, along with friends Joey Bishop, Peter Lawford,
and Sammy Davis, Jr. formed the Rat Pack, so-called after an earlier group of social
friends, the Holmby Hills Rat Pack centered on Humphrey Bogart and Lauren Bacall, of
which Sinatra had been a member. (The Martin-Sinatra-Davis-Lawford-Bishop group
referred to themselves as "The Summit" or "The Clan" and never as "The Rat Pack",
although this has remained their identity in popular imagination.) The men made films
together, formed part of the Hollywood social scene, and were politically influential
(through Lawford's marriage to Patricia Kennedy, sister of President John F. Kennedy)
